The bond formed, as a result of the electrostatic attraction between the positive and negative ions was termed as the electrovalent bond.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "The electrovalence is thus equal to the number of unit charge(s) on the ion.", "fibs": ["electrovalence"]}
{"text": "Thus, calcium is assigned a positive electrovalence of two, while chlorine a negative electrovalence of one.", "fibs": ["calcium"]}
{"text": "Kössel’s postulations provide the basis for the modern concepts regarding ion-formation by electron transfer and the formation of ionic crystalline compounds.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "His views have proved to be of great value in the understanding and systematisation of the ionic compounds.", "fibs": ["value"]}
{"text": "At the same time he did recognise the fact that a large number of compounds did not fit into these concepts.", "fibs": ["time"]}
{"text": "4.1.1	Octet Rule
Kössel and Lewis in 1916 developed an important theory of chemical combination between atoms known as electronic theory of chemical bonding.", "fibs": ["theory"]}
{"text": "According to this, atoms  can combine either by transfer of valence electrons from one atom to another (gaining or losing) or by sharing of valence electrons in order to have an octet in their valence shells.", "fibs": ["transfer"]}
{"text": "This is known as octet rule.", "fibs": ["octet"]}
{"text": "4.1.2	Covalent Bond
Langmuir (1919) refined the Lewis postulations by abandoning the idea of the stationary cubical arrangement of the octet, and by introducing the term covalent bond.", "fibs": ["idea"]}
{"text": "The Lewis-Langmuir theory can be understood by considering the formation of the chlorine molecule,Cl2.", "fibs": ["theory"]}
{"text": "The Cl atom with electronic configuration, [Ne]3s2 3p5, is one electron short of the argon configuration.", "fibs": ["atom"]}
{"text": "The formation of the Cl­2 molecule can be understood in terms of the sharing of a pair of electrons between the two chlorine atoms, each chlorine atom contributing one electron to the shared pair.", "fibs": ["formation"]}
{"text": "In the process both chlorine atoms attain the outer shell octet of the nearest  noble gas (i.e., argon).", "fibs": ["process"]}
{"text": "or Cl – Cl 





