{"text": "Such structures are referred to as Lewis dot structures.", "fibs": ["dot"]}
{"text": "The Lewis dot structures can be written for other molecules also, in which the combining atoms may be identical or different.", "fibs": ["dot"]}
{"text": "The important conditions being that:
•	Each bond is formed as a result of sharing of an electron pair between the atoms.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "•	Each combining atom contributes at least one electron to the shared pair.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "•	The combining atoms attain the outer-shell noble gas configurations as a result of the sharing of electrons.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "•	Thus in water and carbon tetrachloride molecules, formation of covalent bonds can be represented as:





Thus, when two atoms share one electron pair they are said to be joined by a single covalent bond.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "The formation of multiple bonds envisages sharing of more than one electron pair between two atoms.", "fibs": ["formation"]}
{"text": "If two atoms share two pairs of electrons, the covalent bond between them is called a double bond.", "fibs": ["share"]}
{"text": "For example, in the carbon dioxide molecule, we have two double bonds between the carbon and oxygen atoms.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Similarly in ethene molecule the two carbon atoms are joined by a double bond.", "fibs": ["ethene"]}
{"text": "When combining atoms share three electron pairs as in the case of two nitrogen atoms in the N2 molecule and the two carbon atoms in the ethyne molecule, a triple bond is formed.", "fibs": ["share"]}
