{"text": "4.1.4	Formal Charge
Lewis dot structures, in general, do not represent the actual shapes of the molecules.", "fibs": ["dot"]}
{"text": "In case of polyatomic ions, the net charge is possessed by the ion as a whole and not by a particular atom.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "It is, however, feasible to assign a formal charge on each atom.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "The formal charge of an atom in a polyatomic molecule or ion may be defined as the difference between the number of valence electrons of that atom in an isolated or free state and the number of electrons assigned to that atom in the Lewis structure.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "It is expressed as :

The counting is based on the assumption that the atom in the molecule owns one electron of each shared pair and both the electrons of a lone pair.", "fibs": ["assumption"]}
{"text": "Let us consider the ozone molecule (O3).", "fibs": ["ozone"]}
{"text": "The Lewis structure of O3 may be drawn as :














The atoms have been numbered as 1, 2 and 3.", "fibs": ["structure"]}
{"text": "The formal charge on:
•	The central O atom marked 1
