Hence, we represent O3 along with the formal charges as follows:





We must understand that formal charges do not indicate real charge separation within the molecule.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "Indicating the charges on the atoms in the Lewis structure only helps in keeping track of the valence electrons in the molecule.", "fibs": ["structure"]}
{"text": "Formal charges help in the selection of the lowest energy structure from a number of possible Lewis structures for a given species.", "fibs": ["selection"]}
{"text": "Generally the lowest energy structure is the one with the smallest formal charges on the atoms.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "The formal charge is a factor based on a pure covalent view of bonding in which electron pairs are shared equally by neighbouring atoms.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "4.1.5	Limitations of the Octet Rule
The octet rule, though useful, is not universal.", "fibs": ["octet"]}
{"text": "It is quite useful for understanding the structures of most of the organic compounds and it applies mainly to the second period elements of the periodic table.", "fibs": ["understanding"]}
{"text": "There are three types of exceptions to the octet rule.", "fibs": ["octet"]}
{"text": "The incomplete octet of the central atom
In some compounds, the number of electrons surrounding the central atom is less than eight.", "fibs": ["octet"]}
{"text": "This is especially the case with elements having less than four valence electrons.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "Examples are LiCl, BeH2 and BCl3.", "fibs": ["LiCl"]}
{"text": "Li, Be and B have 1,2 and 3 valence electrons only.", "fibs": ["valence"]}
{"text": "Some other such compounds are AlCl3 and BF3.", "fibs": ["AlCl3"]}
{"text": "Odd-electron molecules
In molecules with an odd number of electrons like nitric oxide, NO and nitrogen dioxide, NO2, the octet rule is not satisfied for all the atoms



The expanded octet
Elements in and beyond the third period of the periodic table have, apart from 3s and 3p orbitals, 3d orbitals also available for bonding.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "In a number of compounds of these elements there are more than eight valence electrons around the central atom.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "This is termed as the expanded octet.", "fibs": ["octet"]}
{"text": "Obviously the octet rule does not apply in such cases.", "fibs": ["octet"]}
{"text": "Some of the examples of such compounds are: PF5, SF6, H2SO4 and a number of coordination compounds.", "fibs": ["PF5"]}
{"text": "Interestingly, sulphur also forms many compounds in which the octet rule is obeyed.", "fibs": ["sulphur"]}
{"text": "In sulphur dichloride, the S atom has an octet of electrons around it.", "fibs": ["sulphur"]}
{"text": "Other drawbacks of the octet theory 
•	It is clear that octet rule is based upon the chemical inertness of noble gases.", "fibs": ["octet"]}
{"text": "However, some noble gases (for example xenon and krypton) also combine with oxygen and fluorine to form a number of compounds like XeF2, KrF2, XeOF2 etc.,
•	This theory does not account for the shape of molecules.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "•	It does not explain the relative stability of the molecules being totally silent about the energy of a molecule.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "4.2	Ionic or Electrovalent Bond 
From the Kössel and Lewis treatment of the formation of an ionic bond, it follows that the formation of ionic compounds would primarily depend upon:
•	The ease of formation of the positive and negative ions from the respective neutral atoms;
•	The arrangement of the positive and negative ions in the solid, that is, the lattice of the crystalline compound.", "fibs": ["treatment"]}
{"text": "The formation of a positive ion involves ionization, i.e.,  removal of electron(s) from the neutral atom and that of the negative ion involves the addition of electron(s) to the neutral atom.", "fibs": ["formation"]}
{"text": "M(g)  →  M+(g) + e– ; 
Ionization enthalpy 
X(g) + e–  →  X – (g) ; 
Electron gain enthalpy
M+(g)  + X –(g)  →  MX(s)
The electron gain enthalpy, ∆egH, is the enthalpy change (Unit 3), when a gas phase atom in its ground state gains an electron.", "fibs": ["M(g"]}
{"text": "The electron gain process may be exothermic or endothermic.", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "The ionization, on the other hand, is always endothermic.", "fibs": ["ionization"]}
{"text": "Electron affinity, is the negative of the energy change accompanying electron gain.", "fibs": ["affinity"]}
{"text": "Obviously ionic bonds will be formed more easily between elements with comparatively low ionization enthalpies and elements with comparatively high negative value of electron gain enthalpy.", "fibs": ["ionization"]}
{"text": "The ammonium ion, NH4+ (made up of two non-metallic elements) is an exception.", "fibs": ["ammonium"]}
{"text": "It forms the cation of a number of ionic compounds.", "fibs": ["cation"]}
{"text": "Ionic compounds in the crystalline state consist of orderly three-dimensional arrangements of cations and anions held together by coulombic interaction energies.", "fibs": ["state"]}
{"text": "These compounds crystallise in different crystal structures determined by the size of the ions, their packing arrangements and other factors.", "fibs": ["crystal"]}
{"text": "The crystal structure of sodium chloride, NaCl (rock salt), for example is shown below.", "fibs": ["crystal"]}
{"text": "Rock salt structure
In ionic solids, the sum of the electron gain enthalpy and the ionization enthalpy may be positive but still the crystal structure gets stabilized due to the energy released in the formation of the crystal lattice.", "fibs": ["salt"]}
{"text": "For example: the ionization enthalpy for Na+(g) formation from Na(g) is 495.8 kJ mol–1 ; while the electron gain enthalpy for the change Cl(g) + e–→  Cl– (g) is, – 348.7 kJ mol–1 only.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "The sum of the two, 147.1 kJ mol-1 is more than compensated for by the enthalpy of lattice formation of NaCl(s) (–788 kJ mol–1).", "fibs": ["sum"]}
{"text": "Therefore, the energy released in the processes is more than the energy absorbed.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "Thus a qualitative measure of the stability of an ionic compound is provided by its enthalpy of  lattice formation and not simply by achieving octet of electrons around the ionic species in gaseous state.", "fibs": ["measure"]}
{"text": "Since lattice enthalpy plays a key role in the formation of ionic compounds, it is important that we learn more about it.", "fibs": ["lattice"]}
{"text": "4.2.1	Lattice Enthalpy
The Lattice Enthalpy of an ionic solid is defined as the energy required to completely separate one mole of a solid ionic compound into gaseous constituent ions.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "For example, the lattice enthalpy of NaCl is 788 kJ mol–1.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "This means that 788 kJ of energy is required to separate one mole of solid NaCl into one mole of Na+ (g) and one mole of Cl– (g) to an infinite distance.", "fibs": ["kJ"]}
{"text": "This process involves both the attractive forces between ions of opposite charges and the repulsive forces between ions of like charge.", "fibs": ["process"]}
{"text": "The solid crystal being three-dimensional; it is not possible to calculate lattice enthalpy directly from the interaction of forces of attraction and repulsion only.", "fibs": ["crystal"]}
{"text": "Factors associated with the crystal geometry have to be included.", "fibs": ["crystal"]}
{"text": "4.3 Bond Parameters
4.3.1  Bond Length
Bond length is defined as the equilibrium distance between the nuclei of two bonded atoms in a molecule.", "fibs": ["Length"]}
{"text": "Bond lengths are measured by spectroscopic, X-ray diffraction and electron-diffraction techniques about which you will learn in higher classes.", "fibs": ["spectroscopic"]}
{"text": "Each atom of the bonded pair contributes to the bond length (Fig.", "fibs": ["atom"]}
{"text": "In the case of a covalent bond, the contribution from each atom is called the covalent radius of that atom.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "The covalent radius is measured approximately as the radius of an atom’s core which is in contact with the core of an adjacent atom in a bonded situation.", "fibs": ["covalent"]}
{"text": "The covalent radius is half of the distance between two similar atoms joined by a covalent bond in the same molecule.", "fibs": ["covalent"]}
{"text": "The van der Waals radius represents the overall size of the atom which includes its valence shell in a nonbonded situation.", "fibs": ["radius"]}
{"text": "Further, the van der Waals radius is half of the distance between two similar atoms in separate molecules in a solid.", "fibs": ["radius"]}
