In the Lewis description of covalent bond, the Bond Order is given by the number of bonds between the two atoms in a molecule.", "fibs": ["bond"]}
{"text": "The bond order, for example in H2 (with a single shared electron pair), in O2 (with two shared electron pairs) and in N2 (with three shared electron pairs) is 1,2,3 respectively.", "fibs": ["bond"]}
{"text": "Similarly in CO (three shared electron pairs between C and O) the bond order is 3.", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "For N2, bond order is 3 and its  is 946 kJ mol–1; being one of the highest for a diatomic molecule.", "fibs": ["bond"]}
{"text": "Isoelectronic molecules and ions have identical bond orders; for example, F2 and O2 2– have bond order 1.", "fibs": ["bond"]}
{"text": "N2, CO and NO+ have bond order 3.", "fibs": ["bond"]}
{"text": "A general correlation useful for understanding the stablities of molecules  is that: with increase in bond order, bond enthalpy increases and bond length decreases.", "fibs": ["correlation"]}
{"text": "4.3.5	Resonance Structures
It is often observed that a single Lewis structure is inadequate for the representation of a molecule in conformity with its experimentally determined parameters.", "fibs": ["structure"]}
{"text": "For example, the ozone, O3 molecule can be equally represented by the structures I and II shown below:
In both structures we have a O–O single bond and a O=O double bond.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "The normal O–O and O=O bond lengths are 148 pm and 121 pm respectively.", "fibs": ["bond"]}
{"text": "Experimentally determined oxygen-oxygen bond lengths in the O3 molecule are same (128 pm).", "fibs": ["bond"]}
{"text": "Thus the oxygen-oxygen bonds in the O3 molecule are intermediate between a double and a single bond.", "fibs": ["molecule"]}
{"text": "The concept of resonance was introduced to deal with the type of difficulty experienced in the depiction of accurate structures of molecules like O3.", "fibs": ["concept"]}
{"text": "According to the concept of resonance, whenever a single Lewis structure cannot describe a molecule accurately, a number of structures with similar energy, positions of nuclei, bonding and non-bonding pairs of electrons are taken as the canonical structures of the hybrid which describes the molecule accurately.", "fibs": ["concept"]}
{"text": "Thus for O3, the two structures shown above constitute the canonical structures or resonance structures and their hybrid i.e., the III structure represents the structure of O3 more accurately.", "fibs": ["resonance"]}
{"text": "This is also called resonance hybrid.", "fibs": ["resonance"]}
{"text": "Resonance is represented by a double headed arrow.", "fibs": ["Resonance"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "4.3  Resonance in the O3 molecule (structures I and II represent the two canonical forms while the structure III  is the resonance hybrid)



Some of the other examples of resonance structures are provided by the carbonate ion and the carbon dioxide molecule.", "fibs": ["molecule"]}
{"text": "Problem 4.3 
Explain the structure of CO32– ion in terms of resonance.", "fibs": ["structure"]}
{"text": "Solution
The single Lewis structure based on the presence of two single bonds and one double bond between carbon and oxygen atoms is inadequate to represent the molecule accurately as it represents unequal bonds.", "fibs": ["structure"]}
{"text": "According to the experimental findings, all carbon to oxygen bonds in CO32– are equivalent.", "fibs": ["carbon"]}
{"text": "Therefore the carbonate ion is best described as a resonance hybrid of the canonical forms I, II, and III shown below.", "fibs": ["ion"]}
{"text": "Fig.4.4	Resonance in CO32–, I, II and III represent the three canonical forms.", "fibs": ["CO32–"]}
{"text": "Problem 4.4  
Explain the structure of CO2 molecule.", "fibs": ["structure"]}
{"text": "Solution
The experimentally determined carbon to oxygen bond length in CO2 is 115 pm.", "fibs": ["carbon"]}
{"text": "The lengths of a normal carbon to oxygen double bond (C=O) and carbon to oxygen triple bond (C≡O) are 121 pm and 110 pm respectively.", "fibs": ["carbon"]}
{"text": "The carbon-oxygen bond lengths in CO2 (115 pm) lie between the values for C=O and C≡O.", "fibs": ["bond"]}
{"text": "Obviously, a single Lewis structure cannot depict this position and it becomes necessary to write more than one Lewis structures and to consider that the structure of CO2 is best described as a hybrid of the canonical or resonance  forms I, II  and III.", "fibs": ["structure"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "4.5	Resonance in CO2 molecule, I, II and III represent the three canonical forms.", "fibs": ["CO2"]}
{"text": "In general, it may be stated that 
•	Resonance stabilizes the molecule as the energy of the resonance hybrid is less than the energy of any single cannonical structure; and,
•	Resonance averages the bond characteristics as a whole.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "Thus the energy of the O3 resonance hybrid is lower than either of the two cannonical froms I and II (Fig 4.3).", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "Many misconceptions are associated with resonance and the same need to be dispelled.", "fibs": ["resonance"]}
{"text": "You should remember that :
•	The cannonical forms have no real existence.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "•	The molecule does not exist for a certain fraction of time in one cannonical form and for other fractions of time in other cannonical forms.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "• There is no such  equilibrium between the cannonical forms as we have between tautomeric forms (keto and enol) in tautomerism.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "• The molecule as such has a single structure which is the resonance hybrid of the cannonical forms and which cannot as such be depicted by a single Lewis structure.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "4.3.6	Polarity of Bonds 
The existence of a hundred percent ionic or covalent bond represents an ideal situation.", "fibs": ["existence"]}
{"text": "In reality no bond or a compound is either completely covalent or ionic.", "fibs": ["reality"]}
{"text": "Even in case of covalent bond between two hydrogen atoms, there is some ionic character.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "When covalent bond is formed between two similar atoms, for example in H2, O2, Cl2, N2 or F2, the shared pair of electrons is equally attracted by the two atoms.", "fibs": ["covalent"]}
{"text": "As a result electron pair is situated exactly between the two identical nuclei.", "fibs": ["result"]}
{"text": "The bond so formed is called nonpolar covalent bond.", "fibs": ["bond"]}
{"text": "Contrary to this in case of a heteronuclear molecule like HF, the shared electron pair between the two atoms gets displaced more towards fluorine since the electronegativity of fluorine (Unit 3) is far greater than that of hydrogen.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "The resultant covalent bond is a polar covalent bond.", "fibs": ["covalent"]}
{"text": "As a result of polarisation, the molecule possesses the dipole moment (depicted below) which can be defined as the product of the magnitude of the charge and the distance between the centres of positive and negative charge.", "fibs": ["result"]}
{"text": "It is usually designated by a Greek letter ‘µ’.", "fibs": ["letter"]}
{"text": "Mathematically, it is expressed as follows :
Dipole moment (µ) = charge (Q) × distaTable 4.2	Average Bond Lengths for Some Single, Double and Triple Bonds Bond Type Covalent Bond Lengthnce of  	                                                separation (r)
Dipole moment is usually expressed in Debye units (D).", "fibs": ["moment"]}
{"text": "The conversion factor is
	1 D = 3.33564 × 10–30  C m
where C is coulomb and m is meter.", "fibs": ["conversion"]}
{"text": "Further dipole moment is a vector quantity and by convention it is depicted by a small arrow with tail on the negative centre and head pointing towards the positive centre.", "fibs": ["moment"]}
{"text": "But in chemistry presence of dipole moment is represented by the crossed arrow () put on Lewis structure of the molecule.", "fibs": ["chemistry"]}
{"text": "The cross is on positive end and arrow head is on negative end.", "fibs": ["end"]}
{"text": "For example the dipole moment of HF may be represented as :




This arrow symbolises the direction of the shift of electron density in the molecule.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Note that the direction of crossed arrow is opposite to the conventional direction of dipole moment vector.", "fibs": ["direction"]}
{"text": "In case of polyatomic molecules the dipole moment not only depend upon the individual dipole moments of bonds known as bond dipoles but also on the spatial arrangement of various bonds in the molecule.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "In such case, the dipole moment of a molecule is the vector sum of the dipole moments of various bonds.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "For example in H2O molecule, which has a bent structure, the two O–H bonds are oriented at an angle of 104.50.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Net dipole moment of 6.17 × 10–30 C m (1D = 3.33564 × 10–30 C m) is the resultant of the dipole moments of two O–H bonds.", "fibs": ["moment"]}
{"text": "Peter Debye, the Dutch chemist received Nobel prize in 1936 for his work on X-ray diffraction and dipole moments.", "fibs": ["chemist"]}
{"text": "The magnitude of the dipole moment is given in Debye units in order to honour him.", "fibs": ["magnitude"]}
{"text": "Net Dipole moment, µ  = 1.85 D = 1.85 × 3.33564 × 10–30 C m = 6.17 ×10–30 C m
The dipole moment in case of BeF2 is zero.", "fibs": ["moment"]}
{"text": "This is because the two equal bond dipoles point in opposite directions and cancel the effect of each other.", "fibs": ["bond"]}
{"text": "In tetra-atomic molecule,  for example in BF3, the dipole moment is zero although the  B – F bonds are oriented at an angle of 120o to one another, the three bond moments give a net sum of zero as the resultant of any two is equal and opposite to the third.", "fibs": ["molecule"]}
{"text": "Let us study an interesting case of NH3 and NF3 molecule.", "fibs": ["study"]}
{"text": "Both the molecules have pyramidal shape with a lone pair of electrons on nitrogen atom.", "fibs": ["shape"]}
{"text": "Although fluorine is more electronegative than nitrogen, the resultant dipole moment of NH3 ( 4.90 × 10–30 C m) is greater than that of NF3 (0.8 × 10–30 C m).", "fibs": ["fluorine"]}
{"text": "This is because, in case of NH3 the orbital dipole due to lone pair is in the same direction as the resultant dipole moment of the N – H bonds, whereas in NF3 the orbital dipole is in the direction opposite to the resultant dipole moment of the three N–F bonds.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "The orbital dipole because of lone pair  decreases the effect of the resultant N – F bond moments, which results in the low dipole moment of NF3 as represented below :


Dipole moments of some molecules are shown in Table 4.5.", "fibs": ["pair"]}
{"text": "Just as all the covalent bonds have some partial ionic character, the ionic bonds also have partial covalent character.", "fibs": ["covalent"]}
{"text": "The partial covalent character of ionic bonds was discussed by Fajans in terms of the following rules:
•	The smaller the size of the cation and the larger the size of the anion, the greater the covalent character of an ionic bond.", "fibs": ["covalent"]}
{"text": "• The greater the charge on the cation, the greater the covalent character of the ionic bond.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "•	For cations of the same size and charge, the one, with electronic configuration (n-1)dnnso, typical of transition metals, is more polarising than the one with a noble gas configuration, ns2 np6, typical of alkali and alkaline earth metal cations.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "The cation polarises the anion, pulling the electronic charge toward itself and thereby increasing the electronic charge between the two.", "fibs": ["cation"]}
{"text": "This is precisely what happens in a covalent bond, i.e., buildup of electron charge density between the nuclei.", "fibs": ["covalent"]}
{"text": "The polarising power of the cation, the polarisability of the anion and the extent of distortion (polarisation) of anion are the factors, which determine the per cent covalent character of the ionic bond.", "fibs": ["power"]}
{"text": "4.4	The Valence Shell Electron Pair Repulsion (VSEPR) Theory
As already explained, Lewis concept is unable to explain the shapes of molecules.", "fibs": ["VSEPR"]}
{"text": "This theory provides a simple procedure to predict the shapes of covalent molecules.", "fibs": ["theory"]}
{"text": "Sidgwick and Powell in 1940, proposed a simple theory based on the repulsive interactions of the electron pairs in the valence shell of the atoms.", "fibs": ["theory"]}
{"text": "Table 4.5 Dipole Moments of Selected Molecules

The main postulates of VSEPR theory are as follows:
•	The shape of a molecule depends upon the number of valence shell electron pairs (bonded or nonbonded) around the central atom.", "fibs": ["Table"]}
{"text": "•	Pairs of electrons in the valence shell repel one another since their electron clouds are negatively charged.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "•	These pairs of electrons tend to occupy such positions in space that minimise repulsion and thus maximise distance between them.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "•	The valence shell is taken as a sphere with the electron pairs localising on the spherical surface at maximum distance from one another.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "•	A multiple bond is treated as if it is a single electron pair and the two or three electron pairs of a multiple bond are treated as a single super pair.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "•	Where two or more resonance structures can represent a molecule, the VSEPR model is applicable to any such structure.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "The repulsive interaction of electron pairs decrease in the order:
Lone pair (lp) – Lone pair (lp) > Lone pair (lp) – Bond pair (bp) > Bond pair (bp) – Bond pair (bp) 
Nyholm and Gillespie (1957) refined the VSEPR model by explaining the important difference between the lone pairs and bonding pairs of electrons.", "fibs": ["interaction"]}
{"text": "While the lone pairs are localised on the central atom, each bonded pair is shared between two atoms.", "fibs": ["atom"]}
{"text": "As a result, the lone pair electrons in a molecule occupy more space as compared to the bonding pairs of electrons.", "fibs": ["result"]}
{"text": "This results in greater repulsion between lone pairs of electrons as compared to the lone pair - bond pair and bond pair - bond pair repulsions.", "fibs": ["repulsion"]}
{"text": "These repulsion effects result in deviations from idealised shapes and alterations in bond angles in molecules.", "fibs": ["repulsion"]}
{"text": "For the prediction of geometrical shapes of molecules with the help of VSEPR theory, it is convenient to divide molecules into two categories as (i) molecules in which the central atom has no lone pair and (ii) molecules in which the central atom has one or more lone pairs.", "fibs": ["prediction"]}
{"text": "Table 4.6 (page114) shows the arrangement of electron pairs about a central atom A (without any lone pairs) and geometries of some molecules/ions of the type AB.", "fibs": ["Table"]}
{"text": "Table 4.7 (page 115) shows shapes of some simple molecules and ions in which the central atom has one or more lone pairs.", "fibs": ["Table"]}
{"text": "Table 4.8 (page 116) explains the reasons for the distortions in the geometry of the molecule.", "fibs": ["Table"]}
{"text": "As depicted in Table 4.6, in the compounds of AB2, AB3, AB4, AB5 and AB6, the arrangement of electron pairs and the B atoms around the central atom A are : linear, trigonal planar, tetrahedral, trigonal-bipyramidal and octahedral, respectively.", "fibs": ["Table"]}
{"text": "Such arrangement can be seen in the molecules like BF3 (AB3), CH4 (AB4) and PCl5 (AB5) as depicted below by their ball and stick models.", "fibs": ["arrangement"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "4.6	The shapes of  molecules in which central atom has no lone pair




The VSEPR Theory is able to predict geometry of a large number of molecules, especially the compounds of p-block elements accurately.", "fibs": ["atom"]}
{"text": "It is also quite successful in determining the geometry quite-accurately even when the energy difference between possible structures is very small.", "fibs": ["geometry"]}
{"text": "The theoretical basis of the VSEPR theory regarding the effects of electron pair repulsions on molecular shapes is not clear and continues to be a subject of doubt and discussion.", "fibs": ["basis"]}
