4.5	Valence Bond Theory 
As we know that Lewis approach helps in writing the structure of molecules but it fails to explain the formation of chemical bond.", "fibs": ["Table"]}
{"text": "It also does not give any reason for the difference in bond dissociation enthalpies and bond lengths in molecules like H2 (435.8 kJ mol-1, 74 pm) and F2 (155 kJ mol-1, 144 pm), although in both the cases a single covalent bond is formed by the sharing of an electron pair between the respective atoms.", "fibs": ["reason"]}
{"text": "It also gives no idea about the shapes of polyatomic molecules.", "fibs": ["idea"]}
{"text": "Similarly the VSEPR theory gives the geometry of simple molecules but theoretically, it does not explain them and also it has limited applications.", "fibs": ["VSEPR"]}
{"text": "To overcome these limitations the two important theories based on quantum mechanical principles are introduced.", "fibs": ["quantum"]}
{"text": "These are valence bond (VB) theory and molecular orbital (MO) theory.", "fibs": ["valence"]}
{"text": "Valence bond theory was introduced by Heitler and London (1927) and developed further by Pauling and others.", "fibs": ["bond"]}
{"text": "A discussion of the valence bond theory is based on the knowledge of atomic orbitals, electronic configurations of elements (Units 2), the overlap criteria of atomic orbitals, the hybridization of atomic orbitals and the principles of variation and superposition.", "fibs": ["discussion"]}
{"text": "A rigorous treatment of the VB theory in terms of these aspects is beyond the scope of this book.", "fibs": ["treatment"]}
{"text": "Therefore, for the sake of convenience, valence bond theory has been discussed in terms of qualitative and non-mathematical treatment only.", "fibs": ["sake"]}
{"text": "To start with, let us consider the formation of hydrogen molecule which is the simplest of all molecules.", "fibs": ["formation"]}
{"text": "Consider two hydrogen atoms A and B approaching each other having nuclei NA  and NB and electrons present in them are represented by eA and eB.", "fibs": ["hydrogen"]}
{"text": "When the two atoms are at large distance from each other, there is no interaction between them.", "fibs": ["distance"]}
{"text": "As these two atoms approach each other, new attractive and repulsive forces begin to operate.", "fibs": ["approach"]}
{"text": "Attractive forces arise between:
(i)	nucleus of one atom and its  own electron that is NA – eA and NB– eB.", "fibs": ["nucleus"]}
{"text": "(ii)	nucleus of one atom and electron of other atom i.e., NA– eB, NB– eA.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "Similarly repulsive forces arise between (i) electrons of two atoms like eA – eB, (ii) nuclei of two atoms NA – NB.", "fibs": ["eA"]}
{"text": "Attractive forces tend to bring the two atoms close to each other whereas repulsive forces tend to push them apart (Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "4.7	Forces of attraction and repulsion during the formation of H2 molecule.", "fibs": ["attraction"]}
{"text": "Experimentally it has been found that the magnitude of new attractive force is more than the new repulsive forces.", "fibs": ["magnitude"]}
{"text": "As a result, two atoms approach each other and potential energy decreases.", "fibs": ["result"]}
{"text": "Ultimately a stage is reached where the net force of attraction balances the force of repulsion and system acquires minimum energy.", "fibs": ["stage"]}
{"text": "At this stage two hydrogen atoms are said to be bonded together to form a stable molecule having the bond length of 74 pm.", "fibs": ["stage"]}
{"text": "Since the energy gets released when the bond is formed between two hydrogen atoms, the hydrogen molecule is more stable than that of isolated hydrogen atoms.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "The energy so released is called as bond enthalpy, which is corresponding to minimum in the curve depicted in Fig.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "Conversely, 435.8 kJ of energy is required to dissociate one mole of H2 molecule.", "fibs": ["kJ"]}
{"text": "H2(g) + 435.8 kJ mol–1 → H(g) + H(g)

Fig.", "fibs": ["H2(g"]}
{"text": "4.8 The potential energy curve for the formation of H2 molecule as a function of internuclear distance of the H atoms.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "The minimum in the curve corresponds to the most stable state of H2.", "fibs": ["curve"]}
{"text": "4.5.1 Orbital Overlap Concept 
In the formation of hydrogen molecule, there is a minimum energy state when two hydrogen atoms are so near that their atomic orbitals undergo partial interpenetration.", "fibs": ["formation"]}
{"text": "This partial merging of atomic orbitals is called overlapping of atomic orbitals which results in the pairing of electrons.", "fibs": ["pairing"]}
{"text": "The extent of overlap decides the strength of a covalent bond.", "fibs": ["extent"]}
{"text": "In general, greater the overlap the stronger is the bond formed between two atoms.", "fibs": ["overlap"]}
{"text": "Therefore, according to orbital overlap concept, the formation of a covalent bond between two atoms results by pairing of electrons present in the valence shell having opposite spins.", "fibs": ["overlap"]}
{"text": "4.5.2  Directional Properties of Bonds
As we have already seen, the covalent bond is formed by overlapping of atomic orbitals.", "fibs": ["covalent"]}
{"text": "The molecule of hydrogen is formed due to the overlap of 1s-orbitals of two H atoms.", "fibs": ["molecule"]}
{"text": "In case of polyatomic molecules like CH4, NH3 and H2O, the geometry of the molecules is also important in addition to the bond formation.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "For example why is it so that CH4 molecule has tetrahedral shape and HCH bond angles are 109.5°?", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Why is the shape of NH3 molecule pyramidal ?", "fibs": ["shape"]}
{"text": "The valence bond theory explains the shape, the formation and directional properties of bonds in polyatomic molecules like CH4, NH3 and H2O, etc.", "fibs": ["valence"]}
{"text": "in terms of overlap and hybridisation of atomic orbitals.", "fibs": ["overlap"]}
{"text": "4.5.3	Overlapping of Atomic Orbitals
When orbitals of two atoms come close to form bond, their overlap may be positive, negative or zero depending upon the sign (phase) and direction of orientation of amplitude of orbital wave function in space (Fig.", "fibs": ["form"]}
{"text": "Positive and negative sign on boundary surface diagrams in the Fig.", "fibs": ["sign"]}
{"text": "4.9 show the sign (phase) of orbital wave function and are not related to charge.", "fibs": ["show"]}
{"text": "Orbitals forming bond should have same sign (phase) and orientation in space.", "fibs": ["bond"]}
{"text": "This is called positive overlap.", "fibs": ["overlap"]}
{"text": "Various overlaps of s and p orbitals are depicted in Fig.", "fibs": ["p"]}
{"text": "The criterion of overlap, as the main factor for the formation of covalent bonds applies uniformly to the homonuclear/heteronuclear diatomic molecules and polyatomic molecules.", "fibs": ["criterion"]}
{"text": "We know that the shapes of CH4, NH3, and H2O molecules are tetrahedral, pyramidal and bent respectively.", "fibs": ["CH4"]}
{"text": "It would be therefore interesting to use VB theory to find out if these geometrical shapes can be explained in terms of the orbital overlaps.", "fibs": ["use"]}
{"text": "Let us first consider the CH4 (methane) molecule.", "fibs": ["CH4"]}
{"text": "The electronic configuration of carbon in its ground state is [He]2s2 2p2 which in the excited state becomes [He] 2s1 2px1 2py1 2pz1.", "fibs": ["configuration"]}
{"text": "The energy required for this excitation is compensated by the release of energy due to  overlap between the orbitals of carbon and the hydrogen.The four atomic orbitals of carbon, each with an unpaired electron can overlap with the 1s orbitals of the four H atoms which are also singly occupied.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "This will result in the formation of four C-H bonds.", "fibs": ["result"]}
{"text": "It will, however, be observed that while the three p orbitals of carbon are at 90° to one another, the HCH angle for these will also be 90°.", "fibs": ["p"]}
{"text": "That is three C-H bonds will be oriented at 90° to one another.", "fibs": ["90°"]}
{"text": "The 2s orbital of carbon and the 1s orbital of H are spherically symmetrical and they can overlap in any direction.", "fibs": ["carbon"]}
{"text": "Therefore the direction of the fourth C-H bond cannot be ascertained.", "fibs": ["direction"]}
{"text": "This description does not fit in with the tetrahedral HCH angles of 109.5°.", "fibs": ["description"]}
{"text": "Clearly, it follows that simple atomic orbital overlap does not account for the directional characteristics of bonds in CH4.", "fibs": ["overlap"]}
{"text": "Using similar procedure and arguments, it can be seen that in the case of NH3 and H2O molecules, the HNH and HOH angles should be 90°.", "fibs": ["procedure"]}
{"text": "This is in disagreement with the actual bond angles of 107° and 104.5° in the NH3 and H2O molecules respectively.", "fibs": ["disagreement"]}
{"text": "Fig.4.9 Positive, negative and zero overlaps of s and p atomic orbitals



4.5.4	Types of Overlapping and Nature of Covalent Bonds 
The covalent bond may be classified into two types depending upon the types of overlapping:
(i) Sigma(σ) bond, and (ii) pi(π) bond
(i)	Sigma(σ) bond : This type of covalent bond is formed by the end to end (head-on) overlap of bonding orbitals along the internuclear axis.", "fibs": ["p"]}
{"text": "This is called as head on overlap or axial overlap.", "fibs": ["head"]}
{"text": "•	s-s overlapping : In this case, there is overlap of two half filled s-orbitals along the internuclear axis as shown below :
•	s-p overlapping: This type of overlap occurs between half filled s-orbitals of one atom and half filled p-orbitals of another atom.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "•	p–p overlapping : This type of overlap takes place between half filled p-orbitals of the two approaching atoms.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "(ii)	pi(π ) bond : In the formation of π  bond the atomic orbitals overlap in such a way that their axes remain parallel to each other and perpendicular to the internuclear axis.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "The orbitals formed due to sidewise overlapping consists of two saucer type charged clouds above and below the plane of the participating atoms.", "fibs": ["saucer"]}
{"text": "4.5.5	Strength of Sigma and pi Bonds 
Basically the strength of a bond depends upon the extent of overlapping.", "fibs": ["Strength"]}
{"text": "In case of sigma bond, the overlapping of orbitals takes place to a larger extent.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "Hence, it is stronger as compared to the pi bond where the extent of overlapping occurs to a smaller extent.", "fibs": ["pi"]}
{"text": "Further, it is important to note that in the formation of multiple bonds between two atoms of a molecule, pi bond(s) is formed in addition to a sigma bond.", "fibs": ["note"]}
{"text": "4.6	Hybridisation
In order to explain the characteristic geometrical shapes of polyatomic molecules like CH4, NH3 and H2O etc., Pauling introduced the concept of hybridisation.", "fibs": ["order"]}
{"text": "According to him the atomic orbitals combine to form new set of equivalent orbitals known as hybrid orbitals.", "fibs": ["form"]}
{"text": "Unlike pure orbitals, the hybrid orbitals are used in bond formation.", "fibs": ["bond"]}
{"text": "The phenomenon is known as hybridisation which can be defined as the process of intermixing of the orbitals of slightly different energies so as to redistribute their energies, resulting in the formation of new set of orbitals of equivalent energies and shape.", "fibs": ["phenomenon"]}
{"text": "For example when one 2s and three 2p-orbitals of carbon hybridise, there is the formation of four new sp3 hybrid orbitals.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Salient features of hybridisation: The main features of hybridisation are as under :
1.", "fibs": ["hybridisation"]}
{"text": "The number of hybrid orbitals is equal to the number of the atomic orbitals that get hybridised.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "The hybridised orbitals are always equivalent in energy and shape.", "fibs": ["equivalent"]}
{"text": "These hybrid orbitals are directed in space in some preferred direction to have minimum repulsion between electron pairs and thus a stable arrangement.", "fibs": ["space"]}
{"text": "Therefore, the type of hybridisation indicates the geometry of the molecules.", "fibs": ["type"]}
{"text": "Important conditions for hybridisation 
(i)	The orbitals present in the valence shell of the atom are hybridised.", "fibs": ["hybridisation"]}
{"text": "(ii)	The orbitals undergoing hybridisation should have almost equal energy.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "(iii)	Promotion of electron is not essential condition prior to hybridisation.", "fibs": ["iii"]}
{"text": "(iv)	It is not necessary that only half filled orbitals participate in hybridisation.", "fibs": ["iv"]}
{"text": "In some cases, even filled orbitals of valence shell take part in hybridisation.", "fibs": ["valence"]}
{"text": "4.6.1  Types of Hybridisation 
There are various types of hybridisation involving s, p and d orbitals.", "fibs": ["hybridisation"]}
{"text": "The different types of hybridisation are as under:
(I) sp hybridisation: This type of hybridisation involves the mixing of one s and one p orbital resulting in the formation of two equivalent sp hybrid orbitals.", "fibs": ["hybridisation"]}
{"text": "The suitable orbitals for sp hybridisation are s and pz, if the hybrid orbitals are to lie along the z-axis.", "fibs": ["sp"]}
{"text": "Each sp hybrid orbitals has 50% s-character and 50% p-character.", "fibs": ["sp"]}
{"text": "Such a molecule in which the central atom is sp-hybridised and linked directly to two other central atoms possesses linear geometry.", "fibs": ["molecule"]}
{"text": "This type of hybridisation is also known as diagonal hybridisation.", "fibs": ["type"]}
{"text": "The two sp hybrids point in the opposite direction along the z-axis with projecting positive lobes and very small negative lobes, which provides more effective overlapping resulting in the formation of stronger bonds.", "fibs": ["sp"]}
{"text": "Example of molecule having sp hybridisation 
BeCl2: The ground state electronic configuration of Be is 1s22s2.", "fibs": ["Example"]}
{"text": "In the exited state one of the 2s-electrons is promoted to vacant 2p orbital to account for its bivalency.", "fibs": ["state"]}
{"text": "One 2s and one 2p-orbital gets hybridised to form two sp hybridised orbitals.", "fibs": ["form"]}
{"text": "These two sp hybrid orbitals are oriented in opposite direction forming an angle of 180°.", "fibs": ["sp"]}
{"text": "Each of the sp hybridised orbital overlaps with the 2p-orbital of chlorine axially and form two Be-Cl sigma bonds.", "fibs": ["sp"]}
{"text": "This is shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "Fig.4.10 (a) Formation of sp hybrids from s and p orbitals; (b) Formation of the linear BeCl2   molecule
(II) sp2 hybridisation : In this hybridisation there is involvement of one s and two p-orbitals in order to form three equivalent sp2 hybridised orbitals.", "fibs": ["sp"]}
{"text": "For example, in BCl3 molecule, the ground state electronic configuration of central boron atom is 1s22s22p1.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "In the excited state, one of the 2s electrons is promoted to vacant 2p orbital as a result boron has three unpaired electrons.", "fibs": ["state"]}
{"text": "These three orbitals (one 2s and two 2p) hybridise to form three sp2 hybrid orbitals.", "fibs": ["2p"]}
{"text": "The three hybrid orbitals so formed are oriented in a trigonal planar arrangement and overlap with 2p orbitals of chlorine to form three B-Cl bonds.", "fibs": ["arrangement"]}
{"text": "Therefore, in BCl3 (Fig.", "fibs": ["BCl3"]}
