4.7	Molecular Orbital Theory 
Molecular orbital (MO) theory was developed by F. Hund and R.S.", "fibs": ["geometry"]}
{"text": "The salient features of this theory are :





(i)	The electrons in a molecule are present in the various molecular orbitals as the electrons of atoms are present in the various atomic orbitals.", "fibs": ["theory"]}
{"text": "(ii)	The atomic orbitals of comparable energies and proper symmetry combine to form molecular orbitals.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "(iii)	While an electron in an atomic orbital is influenced by one nucleus, in a molecular orbital it is influenced by two or more nuclei depending upon the number of atoms in the molecule.", "fibs": ["iii"]}
{"text": "Thus, an atomic orbital is monocentric while a molecular orbital is polycentric.", "fibs": ["monocentric"]}
{"text": "(iv)	The number of molecular orbital formed is equal to the number of combining atomic orbitals.", "fibs": ["iv"]}
{"text": "(v)	The bonding molecular orbital has  lower energy and hence greater stability than the corresponding antibonding molecular orbital.", "fibs": ["v"]}
{"text": "(vi)	Just as the electron probability distribution around a nucleus in an atom is given by an atomic orbital, the electron probability distribution around a group of nuclei in a molecule is given by a molecular orbital.", "fibs": ["vi"]}
{"text": "(vii)	The molecular orbitals like atomic orbitals are filled in accordance with the aufbau principle obeying the Pauli’s exclusion principle and the Hund’s rule.", "fibs": ["vii"]}
{"text": "4.7.1	Formation of Molecular Orbitals Linear Combination of Atomic Orbitals (LCAO)
According to wave mechanics, the atomic orbitals can be expressed by wave functions (ψ ’s) which represent the amplitude of the electron waves.", "fibs": ["LCAO"]}
{"text": "These are obtained from the solution of Schrödinger wave equation.", "fibs": ["solution"]}
{"text": "However, since it cannot be solved for any system containing more than one electron, molecular orbitals which are one electron wave functions for molecules are difficult to obtain directly from the solution of Schrödinger wave equation.", "fibs": ["system"]}
{"text": "To overcome this problem, an approximate method known as linear combination of atomic orbitals (LCAO) has been adopted.", "fibs": ["problem"]}
{"text": "Let us apply this method to the homonuclear diatomic hydrogen molecule.", "fibs": ["method"]}
{"text": "Consider the hydrogen molecule consisting of two atoms A and B.", "fibs": ["hydrogen"]}
{"text": "Each hydrogen atom in the ground state has one electron in 1s orbital.", "fibs": ["hydrogen"]}
{"text": "The atomic orbitals of these atoms may be represented by the wave functions ψA and ψB.", "fibs": ["wave"]}
{"text": "Mathematically, the formation of molecular orbitals may be described by the linear combination of atomic orbitals that can take place by addition and by subtraction of wave functions of individual atomic orbitals as shown below :
ψMO = ψA + ψB
Therefore, the two molecular orbitals σ and σ* are formed as :
	σ   =  ψA + ψB
 σ* =  ψA – ψB
The molecular orbital σ formed by the addition of atomic orbitals is called the bonding molecular orbital while the molecular orbital σ* formed by the subtraction of atomic orbital is called antibonding molecular orbital as depicted in Fig.", "fibs": ["formation"]}
{"text": "Fig.4.19	Formation of bonding (σ) and antibonding (σ*) molecular orbitals by the linear combination of atomic orbitals ψA and ψB centered on two atoms A and B respectively.", "fibs": ["σ"]}
{"text": "Qualitatively, the formation of molecular orbitals can be understood in terms of the constructive or destructive interference of the electron waves of the combining atoms.", "fibs": ["formation"]}
{"text": "In the formation of bonding molecular orbital, the two electron waves of the bonding atoms reinforce each other due to constructive interference while in the formation of antibonding molecular orbital, the electron waves cancel each other due to destructive interference.", "fibs": ["formation"]}
{"text": "As a result, the electron density in a bonding molecular orbital is located between the nuclei of the bonded atoms because of which the repulsion between the nuclei is very less while in case of an antibonding molecular orbital, most of the electron density is located away from the space between the nuclei.", "fibs": ["result"]}
{"text": "Infact, there is a nodal plane (on which the electron density is zero) between the nuclei and hence the repulsion between the nuclei is high.", "fibs": ["plane"]}
{"text": "Electrons placed in a bonding molecular orbital tend to hold the nuclei together and stabilise a molecule.", "fibs": ["molecule"]}
{"text": "Therefore, a bonding molecular orbital always possesses lower energy than either of the atomic orbitals that have combined to form it.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "In contrast, the electrons placed in the antibonding molecular orbital destabilise the molecule.", "fibs": ["contrast"]}
{"text": "This is because the mutual repulsion of the electrons in this orbital is more than the attraction between the electrons and the nuclei, which causes a net increase in energy.", "fibs": ["repulsion"]}
{"text": "It may be noted that the energy of the antibonding orbital is raised above the energy of the parent atomic orbitals that have combined and the energy of the bonding orbital has been lowered than the parent orbitals.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "The total energy of two molecular orbitals, however, remains the same as that of two original atomic orbitals.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "4.7.2	Conditions for the Combination of Atomic Orbitals
The linear combination of atomic orbitals to form molecular orbitals takes place only if the following conditions are satisfied:
1.", "fibs": ["combination"]}
{"text": "The combining atomic orbitals must have the same or nearly the same energy.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "This means that 1s orbital can combine with another 1s orbital but not with 2s orbital because the energy of 2s orbital is appreciably higher than that of 1s orbital.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "The combining atomic orbitals must have the same symmetry about the molecular axis.", "fibs": ["symmetry"]}
{"text": "By convention z-axis is taken as the molecular axis.", "fibs": ["convention"]}
{"text": "It is important to note that atomic orbitals having same or nearly the same energy will not combine if they do not have the same symmetry.", "fibs": ["note"]}
{"text": "For example, 2pz orbital of one atom can combine with 2pz orbital of the other atom but not with the 2px or 2py orbitals because of their different symmetries.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "The combining atomic orbitals  must overlap to the maximum extent.", "fibs": ["overlap"]}
{"text": "Greater the extent of overlap, the greater will be the electron-density between the nuclei of a molecular orbital.", "fibs": ["extent"]}
{"text": "4.7.3	Types of Molecular Orbitals
Molecular orbitals of diatomic molecules are designated as σ (sigma), π (pi), δ (delta), etc.", "fibs": ["σ"]}
{"text": "In this nomenclature, the sigma (σ) molecular orbitals are symmetrical around the bond-axis while pi (π) molecular orbitals are not symmetrical.", "fibs": ["nomenclature"]}
{"text": "For example, the linear combination of 1s orbitals centered on two nuclei produces two molecular orbitals which are symmetrical around the bond-axis.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Such molecular orbitals are of the σ type and are designated as σ1s and σ*1s [Fig.", "fibs": ["σ"]}
