{"text": "4.7.5	Electronic Configuration and Molecular Behaviour
The distribution of electrons among various molecular orbitals is called the electronic configuration of the molecule.", "fibs": ["Behaviour"]}
{"text": "From the electronic configuration of the molecule, it is possible to get important information about the molecule as discussed below.", "fibs": ["configuration"]}
{"text": "Stability of Molecules:  If Nb is the number of electrons occupying  bonding orbitals and Na the number occupying the antibonding orbitals, then





(i)	the molecule is stable if Nb is greater than Na, and
(ii)	the molecule is unstable if Nb is less than Na.", "fibs": ["Stability"]}
{"text": "In (i) more bonding orbitals are occupied and so the bonding influence is stronger and a stable molecule results.", "fibs": ["influence"]}
{"text": "In (ii) the antibonding influence is stronger and therefore the molecule is unstable.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "Bond order
Bond order (b.o.)", "fibs": ["order"]}
{"text": "is defined as one half the difference between the number of electrons present in the bonding and the antibonding orbitals i.e.,
Bond order (b.o.)", "fibs": ["half"]}
{"text": "= ½ (Nb–Na)
The rules discussed above regarding the stability of the molecule can be restated in terms of bond order as follows: A positive bond order (i.e., Nb > Na) means a stable molecule while a negative (i.e., Nb<Na) or zero (i.e., Nb = Na) bond order means an unstable molecule.", "fibs": ["½"]}
{"text": "Nature of the bond  
Integral bond order values of 1, 2 or 3 correspond to single, double or triple bonds respectively as studied in the classical concept.", "fibs": ["bond"]}
{"text": "Bond-length  
The bond order between two atoms in a molecule may be taken as an approximate measure of the bond length.", "fibs": ["bond"]}
{"text": "The bond length decreases as bond order increases.", "fibs": ["bond"]}
{"text": "Magnetic nature 
If all the molecular orbitals in a molecule are doubly occupied, the substance is diamagnetic (repelled by magnetic field).", "fibs": ["nature"]}
{"text": "However if one or more molecular orbitals are singly occupied it is paramagnetic (attracted by magnetic field), e.g., O2 molecule.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "4.8	BONDING IN SOME HOMONUCLEAR DIATOMIC MOLECULES
In this section we shall discuss bonding in some homonuclear diatomic molecules.", "fibs": ["BONDING"]}
{"text": "Hydrogen molecule (H2 ): It is formed by the combination of two hydrogen atoms.", "fibs": ["Hydrogen"]}
{"text": "Each hydrogen atom has one electron in 1s orbital.", "fibs": ["hydrogen"]}
{"text": "Therefore, in all there are two electrons in hydrogen molecule which are present in σ1s molecular orbital.", "fibs": ["hydrogen"]}
{"text": "So electronic configuration of hydrogen molecule is 
H2 : (σ1s)2
The bond order of H2 molecule can be calculated as given below:

This means that the two hydrogen atoms are bonded together by a single covalent bond.", "fibs": ["configuration"]}
{"text": "The bond dissociation energy of hydrogen molecule has been found to be 438 kJ mol–1 and bond length equal to 74 pm.", "fibs": ["bond"]}
{"text": "Since no unpaired electron is present in hydrogen molecule, therefore, it is diamagnetic.", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "Helium molecule (He2 ): The electronic configuration of helium atom is 1s2.", "fibs": ["Helium"]}
{"text": "Each helium atom contains 2 electrons, therefore, in He2 molecule there would be 4 electrons.", "fibs": ["helium"]}
{"text": "These electrons will be accommodated in σ1s and σ*1s molecular orbitals leading to electronic configuration:
He2 : (σ1s)2 (σ*1s)2
Bond order of He2 is ½(2 – 2) = 0
He2 molecule is therefore unstable and does not exist.", "fibs": ["configuration"]}
{"text": "Similarly, it can be shown that Be2 molecule (σ1s)2 (σ*1s)2 (σ2s)2 (σ*2s)2 also does not exist.", "fibs": ["molecule"]}
{"text": "Lithium molecule (Li2 ): The electronic configuration of lithium is 1s2, 2s1 .", "fibs": ["Lithium"]}
{"text": "The electronic configuration of Li2 molecule, therefore, is Li2 : (σ1s)2 (σ*1s)2 (σ2s)2
The above configuration is also written as KK(σ2s)2 where KK represents the closed K shell structure (σ1s)2 (σ*1s)2.", "fibs": ["configuration"]}
{"text": "From the electronic configuration of Li2 molecule it is clear that there are four electrons present in bonding molecular orbitals and two electrons present in antibonding molecular orbitals.", "fibs": ["configuration"]}
{"text": "Its bond order, therefore, is ½ (4 – 2) = 1.", "fibs": ["bond"]}
{"text": "It means that Li2 molecule is stable and since it has no unpaired electrons it should be diamagnetic.", "fibs": ["molecule"]}
{"text": "Indeed diamagnetic Li2 molecules are known to exist in the vapour phase.", "fibs": ["vapour"]}
{"text": "Carbon molecule (C2 ): The electronic configuration of carbon is 1s2 2s2 2p2.", "fibs": ["molecule"]}
{"text": "The electronic configuration of C2 molecule, therefore, is

The bond order of C2 is ½ (8 – 4) = 2 and C2 should be diamagnetic.", "fibs": ["configuration"]}
{"text": "Diamagnetic C2 molecules have indeed been detected in vapour phase.", "fibs": ["vapour"]}
{"text": "It is important to note that double bond in C2 consists of both pi bonds because of the presence of four electrons in two pi molecular orbitals.", "fibs": ["note"]}
{"text": "In most of the other molecules a double bond is made up of a sigma bond and a pi bond.", "fibs": ["bond"]}
{"text": "In a similar fashion the bonding in N2 molecule can be discussed.", "fibs": ["fashion"]}
