{"text": "4.9 Hydrogen Bonding 
Nitrogen, oxygen and fluorine are the higly electronegative elements.", "fibs": ["Hydrogen"]}
{"text": "When they are attached to a hydrogen atom to form covalent bond, the electrons of the covalent bond are  shifted towards the more electronegative atom.", "fibs": ["hydrogen"]}
{"text": "This partially positively charged hydrogen atom forms a bond with the other more electronegative atom.", "fibs": ["hydrogen"]}
{"text": "This bond is known as hydrogen bond and is weaker than the covalent bond.", "fibs": ["bond"]}
{"text": "For example, in HF molecule, the hydrogen bond exists between hydrogen atom of one molecule and fluorine atom of another molecule as depicted below :

Here, hydrogen bond acts as a bridge between two atoms which holds one atom by covalent bond and the other by hydrogen bond.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Hydrogen bond is represented by a dotted line (– – –) while a solid line represents the covalent bond.", "fibs": ["Hydrogen"]}
{"text": "Thus, hydrogen bond can be defined as the attractive force which binds hydrogen atom of one molecule with the electronegative atom (F, O or N) of another molecule.", "fibs": ["hydrogen"]}
{"text": "4.9.1	Cause of Formation of Hydrogen Bond 
When hydrogen is bonded to strongly electronegative element ‘X’, the electron pair shared between the two atoms moves far away from hydrogen atom.", "fibs": ["Hydrogen"]}
{"text": "As a result the hydrogen atom becomes highly electropositive with respect to the other atom ‘X’.", "fibs": ["result"]}
{"text": "Since there is displacement of electrons towards X, the hydrogen acquires fractional positive charge (δ +) while ‘X’ attain fractional negative charge (δ–).", "fibs": ["displacement"]}
{"text": "This results in the formation of a polar molecule having electrostatic force of attraction  which can be represented as :

The magnitude of H-bonding depends on the physical state of the compound.", "fibs": ["formation"]}
{"text": "It is maximum in the solid state and minimum in the gaseous state.", "fibs": ["state"]}
{"text": "Thus, the hydrogen bonds have strong influence on the structure and properties of the compounds.", "fibs": ["hydrogen"]}
{"text": "4.9.2 Types of H-Bonds
There are two types of H-bonds
(i)	Intermolecular hydrogen bond
(ii)	Intramolecular hydrogen bond
(1) Intermolecular hydrogen bond : It is formed between two different molecules of the same or different compounds.", "fibs": ["hydrogen"]}
{"text": "For example, H-bond in case of HF molecule, alcohol or water molecules, etc.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "(2) Intramolecular hydrogen bond : It is formed when hydrogen atom is in between the two highly electronegative  (F, O, N) atoms present within the same molecule.", "fibs": ["hydrogen"]}
{"text": "For example, in o-nitrophenol the hydrogen is in between the two oxygen atoms.", "fibs": ["example"]}
